Technological determinism includes a wide range of ideas used in practice, including the technological impetus or technological imperative, as well as a strict definition of human destiny, guided by the hidden logic of scientific laws and their manifestation in the field of technology.
Most of the interpretation of technological determination combines two general principles: firstly, the process of technology development itself is not affected by cultural or political factors, and secondly, the technology generates effects in societies that are immanent and not socially conditional.
For example, it can be said that the motor vehicle necessarily leads to the development of the road network.
Since the nationwide network of roads are not economically cost-effective when the number of vehicles is negligible, new production methods are being developed to reduce vehicle operating costs.
